										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="cs-content" class="cs-content"><div id="x-section-1" class="x-section" style="margin: 0px;padding: 15px 0px 0px; background-color: transparent;" ><div id="" class="x-container max width" style="margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;" ><div  class="x-column x-sm x-1-1" style="padding: 0px;" ><img  class="x-img x-img-none"  src="/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Stephen-Redwood.jpg" ></div></div></div><div id="x-section-2" class="x-section" style="margin: 0px;padding: 45px 0px; background-color: transparent;" ><div id="" class="x-container max width" style="margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;" ><div  class="x-column x-sm x-1-1" style="padding: 0px;" ><ul  class="x-block-grid two-up" ><li  class="x-block-grid-item" >I have been at the Tron with Kansas, working on the script with lovely actors Sadie Dixon-Spain, Jessica Phillippi and Beth Frieden. This is part of a week long festival of new writing happening at the Tron in June. <img src="/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Tron-100-Festival_Kansas_Velveteen-Rabbit-240x300.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="300" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-337" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Tron-100-Festival_Kansas_Velveteen-Rabbit-240x300.jpg 240w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Tron-100-Festival_Kansas_Velveteen-Rabbit.jpg 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Tron-100-Festival_Kansas_Velveteen-Rabbit-100x125.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 240px) 100vw, 240px" /><br />
Rippling was a haunting portrayal of a woman yearning for the human contact of the big cities, compared to the isolation of her island home. Daisy Jo Lucas&#8217;s retreat was a comedic treat in a yogic, detox retreat full of people who needed the calm and silence, but weren&#8217;t terribly open to it, and Isla Robertson&#8217;s Coffin Race was an incredibly exciting blurring of genres with a staged radio play brought to life with a cast of people adding all sorts of exciting sound effects.<br />
</li><li  class="x-block-grid-item" ><img loading="lazy" src="/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-331" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi-300x300.jpg 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi-150x150.jpg 150w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi-768x768.jpg 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi-1600x1600.jpg 1600w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi-100x100.jpg 100w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi-1200x1200.jpg 1200w, /wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Kansas_Beth-Frieden_Jessica-Phillippi.jpg 1842w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" />Above is part of tech, where we were furiously trying to light each scene before being kicked out for the next person to light their show (the rush of a festivals!) and next to this, the exciting announcements in the local paper. Having seen all the shows on Kansas day, I can say that they were an absolute treat. </li></ul></div></div></div></div>
]]></content:encoded>
					
